title: Fluxgate — Distributed Rate Limiter & API Gateway
summary: A zero-dependency edge gateway for token-bucket and sliding-window rate limiting, request shaping, and policy enforcement.
meta: | author: Platform Infrastructure Team | tags: rate-limiting, gateway, edge, redis | theme: technical | type: readme | ref: FG-SPEC-2.4 | license: Apache-2.0

toc:

section: 1. Overview
text: Fluxgate is an embeddable HTTP middleware and standalone reverse proxy that enforces per-client request policies at the edge. It runs identically in-process (as a library) and out-of-process (as a sidecar), sharing one policy file and one counter backend.
text: The same policy document drives both deployments, so behaviour in local development matches production byte-for-byte. Counters are kept in a pluggable store (in-memory, Redis, or any backend implementing the Store interface).

sub: 1.1 Why Fluxgate
- Deterministic limits — the algorithm is specified, not heuristic, so a request that passes in staging passes in production.
- One policy, two runtimes — embed it or front it; the policy file is the single source of truth.
- Zero runtime dependencies in the core; backends are opt-in adapters.
- Observable by default — every decision emits a structured event with the matched rule and remaining budget.

sub: 1.2 Status
metric: Stable since | value: 2026-02-18
metric: Latest release | value: 2.4.0
metric: Median decision latency (in-process) | value: 38 | unit: microseconds | trend: down | period: v2.4

info: Fluxgate enforces limits; it does not store request bodies. Treat it as a control-plane component, never as a cache of user data. | type: info

section: 2. Installation
text: Fluxgate ships as a single package with optional backend adapters. Install the core, then add only the adapter you need.

sub: 2.1 As a library
code: ```bash
npm install @fluxgate/core
# optional backends
npm install @fluxgate/redis
```

sub: 2.2 As a sidecar
text: The sidecar is distributed as a static binary and a container image.
code: ```bash
docker pull ghcr.io/fluxgate/gateway:2.4.0
fluxgate serve --policy ./policy.fluxgate --listen 0.0.0.0:8080
```

link: Release notes & checksums | to: https://github.com/fluxgate/fluxgate/releases/tag/v2.4.0
link: Container image (GHCR) | to: https://ghcr.io/fluxgate/gateway

section: 3. Quick Start
text: The following example protects an Express route with a sliding-window limit of 100 requests per minute, keyed by client IP.

code: ```js
import express from "express";
import { Fluxgate, MemoryStore } from "@fluxgate/core";

const gate = new Fluxgate({
  store: new MemoryStore(),
  rules: [
    { match: "/api/*", limit: 100, window: "1m", key: "ip", algorithm: "sliding-window" },
  ],
});

const app = express();
app.use(gate.middleware());
app.get("/api/orders", (req, res) => res.json({ ok: true }));
app.listen(3000);
```

info: In production prefer a shared backend (Redis) over MemoryStore so limits hold across multiple instances. MemoryStore counts per-process only. | type: warning

section: 4. Core Concepts
sub: 4.1 Rules
text: A rule binds a request matcher to a limit, a window, a key extractor, and an algorithm. Rules are evaluated top to bottom; the FIRST rule whose matcher matches wins, and only that rule's limit applies.

sub: 4.2 Keys
text: The key determines what is being limited — a client IP, an API key, a user id, or a composite. Two requests share a budget if and only if they resolve to the same key for the same matched rule.

sub: 4.3 Algorithms
text: Fluxgate supports three counting algorithms, each with a distinct accuracy and memory trade-off.
1. token-bucket — smooth, allows controlled bursts up to the bucket capacity; cheapest to store (two numbers per key).
2. sliding-window — most accurate at the window boundary; stores a small ring of recent timestamps per key.
3. fixed-window — simplest and fastest, but permits up to 2x burst across a window boundary; use only where boundary bursts are acceptable.

definition: token-bucket | meaning: A counter that refills at a steady rate up to a maximum capacity; each request removes one token, and requests are rejected when the bucket is empty.
definition: sliding-window | meaning: A rolling count of requests over the trailing window duration, recomputed on every request for boundary-accurate enforcement.

section: 5. Policy File Format
text: A policy file declares rules, defaults, and backend configuration in one place. The sidecar reads it directly; the library can load it with loadPolicy().

sub: 5.1 Example policy
code: ```yaml
version: 2
backend:
  kind: redis
  url: redis://cache:6379/0
defaults:
  algorithm: sliding-window
  on_exceed: reject        # reject | delay | tag
rules:
  - name: public-api
    match: /api/*
    key: ip
    limit: 100
    window: 1m
  - name: auth-burst
    match: /auth/login
    key: ip
    limit: 5
    window: 30s
    algorithm: token-bucket
    burst: 10
```

sub: 5.2 Configuration reference
text: Every rule and default is one of the keys below. Unspecified per-rule keys inherit from defaults.
| Key | Type | Default | Description |
| match | glob | (required) | Path pattern; first match wins |
| key | enum | ip | One of ip, header:NAME, query:NAME, or composite |
| limit | integer | (required) | Max requests permitted in the window |
| window | duration | 1m | Window length: 30s, 1m, 1h, 24h |
| algorithm | enum | sliding-window | token-bucket, sliding-window, or fixed-window |
| burst | integer | = limit | Bucket capacity for token-bucket only |
| on_exceed | enum | reject | reject (429), delay (queue), or tag (annotate) |

info: A rule with no match is rejected at load time. Run `fluxgate validate ./policy.fluxgate` in CI to catch policy errors before deploy. | type: tip

section: 6. Behaviour on Limit Exceeded
text: When a key exhausts its budget, Fluxgate applies the rule's on_exceed action.
- reject — respond 429 Too Many Requests with a Retry-After header.
- delay — hold the request in a bounded queue until a token is available, or time out.
- tag — allow the request but attach an X-Fluxgate-Throttled header for downstream handling.

requirement: All responses MUST carry the X-RateLimit-Limit, X-RateLimit-Remaining, and X-RateLimit-Reset headers. | level: MUST | ref: RFC-6585
requirement: A 429 response MUST include a Retry-After header expressed in seconds. | level: MUST | ref: RFC-6585
requirement: Clock skew between instances SHOULD NOT exceed 250ms when using a shared backend. | level: SHOULD

section: 7. Observability
text: Every decision emits a structured event. Subscribe with gate.on("decision", handler) in-process, or scrape the Prometheus endpoint from the sidecar.

code: ```json
{
  "ts": "2026-06-24T09:14:02Z",
  "rule": "public-api",
  "key": "ip:203.0.113.7",
  "decision": "reject",
  "remaining": 0,
  "reset_in_ms": 4120
}
```

metric: Events emitted per decision | value: 1
metric: Prometheus scrape interval (recommended) | value: 15 | unit: seconds

section: 8. Performance & Limits
text: Benchmarks below are single-core, warm cache, measured on the reference hardware described in the repository.
| Algorithm | Decisions/sec | Bytes/key | Boundary accuracy |
| token-bucket | 2,100,000 | 24 | exact |
| sliding-window | 1,450,000 | 96 | exact |
| fixed-window | 2,600,000 | 16 | approximate |

risk: Hot-key contention | severity: medium | mitigation: shard the backend by key prefix or enable local pre-aggregation
risk: Backend outage stalls decisions | severity: high | mitigation: configure fail-open or fail-closed per rule explicitly

info: Default failure mode is fail-closed (deny on backend error). For availability-critical public endpoints, set fail_open: true per rule and accept that limits relax during an outage. | type: warning

section: 9. Backend Adapters
text: A backend implements the Store interface: increment, peek, and reset. Adapters ship separately so the core stays dependency-free.
sla: Redis adapter p99 round-trip | target: 2ms | priority: P2
sla: In-memory adapter p99 round-trip | target: 50us | priority: P3

sub: 9.1 Writing your own adapter
code: ```ts
export interface Store {
  increment(key: string, window: number): Promise<{ count: number; resetMs: number }>;
  peek(key: string): Promise<{ count: number; resetMs: number }>;
  reset(key: string): Promise<void>;
}
```

section: 10. Compatibility & Standards
cite: RFC 6585 — Additional HTTP Status Codes | section: 4 (429 Too Many Requests)
cite: RFC 9110 — HTTP Semantics | section: 10.2.3 (Retry-After)
text: Fluxgate targets Node.js 20+ for the library and any platform with a static musl build for the sidecar.

